      "value": "What is Critical Rendering Path?"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "The Critical Rendering Path (CRP) is the sequence of steps the browser takes to convert HTML, CSS, and JavaScript into pixels on the screen."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Why Critical Rendering Path Matters"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "Optimizing the critical rendering path improves page load speed, reduces render-blocking, and enhances user experience."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Steps in Critical Rendering Path"
    },
    {
      "type": "table",
      "value": {
        "headers": ["Step", "Description"],
        "rows": [
          ["DOM", "Parse HTML to create Document Object Model"],
          ["CSSOM", "Parse CSS to create CSS Object Model"],
          ["Render Tree", "Combine DOM and CSSOM"],
          ["Layout", "Calculate positions and sizes"],
          ["Paint", "Render pixels on screen"]
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "DOM Construction"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "The browser parses HTML and builds the DOM tree representing the page structure."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "CSSOM Construction"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "The browser parses CSS and builds the CSSOM, which defines styles for each element."
    },
    {
      "type": "heading",
      "value": "Render Tree"
    },
    {
      "type": "text",
      "value": "The render tree combines DOM and CSSOM to determine what should be displayed on the screen."
    },
